---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="Project Prep Agent">

  <section class="agent-intro">
    <p class="agent-eyebrow">Agent Guide</p>
    <h1 class="agent-h1">Project Prep</h1>
    <p class="agent-summary">
      The Project Prep agent sets up a new design project before you start designing. Give it a
      project name and page type and it runs competitor research, pulls UX review data for the
      equivalent Myprotein page, creates a structured Figma file with the right frames and
      component library linked, and drafts a project brief. The goal is to eliminate the setup
      phase entirely — you should be designing, not gathering reference material and creating blank
      Figma files.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Before you start ────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Before you start</h2>
    <ul class="checklist">
      <li>A clear name for the project and the page type you're redesigning (e.g. "basket redesign", "PDP refresh", "new checkout flow")</li>
      <li>Figma access: the agent creates and structures a Figma file, so the Figma MCP server must be connected in your Claude Code session</li>
      <li>Know which Figma team or project the new file should live in — the agent will ask if you don't specify</li>
      <li>Optional: any existing constraints or context you want baked into the brief (e.g. "mobile-first only", "must use existing component library", "targeting the supplement audience")</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- ── How to trigger ──────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">How to trigger it</h2>
    <p class="guide-body">Use the slash command directly, or describe the project you're starting:</p>
    <div class="trigger-block">
      <code class="trigger-command">/myprotein-prep-agent</code>
    </div>
    <div class="trigger-examples">
      <span class="trigger-chip">"prep for the basket redesign"</span>
      <span class="trigger-chip">"set up a Figma file for the checkout"</span>
      <span class="trigger-chip">"I need to redesign the PDP"</span>
      <span class="trigger-chip">"start a new design project for the search page"</span>
    </div>
    <p class="guide-body guide-body--tip">The more context you give up front — page type, audience, constraints — the less the agent needs to ask before it starts. A phrase like "prep for the basket redesign, mobile-first, existing component library" will kick off without any follow-up questions.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Step-by-step walkthrough ───────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Step-by-step walkthrough</h2>
    <ol class="steps">
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">1</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Project scope is confirmed</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            The agent confirms the page type and any constraints you've specified. If you haven't
            told it which Figma project to use, it will list your available Figma projects and ask
            you to pick one. Once confirmed, it proceeds without further questions.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">2</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Competitor research is run</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            The agent triggers a lightweight competitor sweep — it navigates to the equivalent page
            on a set of key competitors (Gymshark, Bulk, TPW, Optimum Nutrition) and captures
            above-the-fold screenshots. This is a faster, lighter version of the full Competitor
            Analysis agent: it's enough to prime you for the design phase without producing a
            complete comparative report. If a full competitor report already exists in this repo
            for the same page type, the agent links to that instead of re-running.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">3</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Existing UX review data is gathered</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            The agent scans the reports in <code>src/pages/reports/</code> for any existing UX
            reviews of the page type you're redesigning. If a recent review exists, it extracts
            the key findings and includes them in the project brief as "known issues to address."
            This connects your design work directly to the evidence already collected.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">4</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Figma file is created and structured</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            The agent creates a new Figma file in your specified project. It sets up the standard
            frame structure — a Cover page, a Research page (with competitor screenshots and UX
            findings imported), a Design page with desktop and mobile frames at the correct Astro
            widths (1440px and 390px), and a Handoff page. The Myprotein component library is
            linked so design tokens and components are available immediately.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">5</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Project brief is drafted</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            The agent writes a project brief as a text block on the Figma Cover page and also as a
            summary in the chat. The brief covers: the problem the redesign is solving (from UX
            review findings), what competitors do that we don't (from competitor research), key
            design constraints, and a suggested success metric. The brief is a starting point —
            edit it directly in Figma once the file is created.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="step">
        <span class="step-number">6</span>
        <div class="step-body">
          <h3 class="step-title">Agent hands back to you</h3>
          <p class="step-desc">
            The agent shares a direct link to the new Figma file and summarises what it created.
            From here you go straight to Figma and start designing. There are no files to commit
            to this repo from a Project Prep run — all output lives in Figma.
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Committing the output ──────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Committing the output</h2>
    <p class="guide-body">
      Project Prep does not produce files that need to be committed to this repo. All output lives
      in the Figma file the agent creates. There is nothing to <code>git add</code> or
      <code>git push</code> after a Project Prep run.
    </p>
    <p class="guide-body">
      If the agent also triggered a competitor analysis as part of setup and saved a report page,
      that file would be committed separately — the agent will tell you if this happened and give
      you the exact commands to use.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Example output ────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Example output</h2>
    <p class="guide-body">
      No Project Prep runs have been logged on this site yet — because the output is a Figma file,
      not a report page. The first time you run the agent, the Figma file link will be shared in
      chat. You can record it here manually if you want a reference.
    </p>
    <div class="no-example">
      No live example yet — run <code>/myprotein-prep-agent</code> to generate the first one.
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Tips and common issues ────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="guide-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Tips and common issues</h2>
    <ul class="tips-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Figma MCP server isn't connected.</strong>
        The agent will fail at step 4 if the Figma MCP server isn't available. Run
        <code>/setup-cowork</code> to check your MCP connections, or go to
        <code>Settings → MCP Servers</code> in Claude Code and confirm the Figma server is listed
        and connected.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Agent creates the Figma file in the wrong project.</strong>
        If you have multiple Figma projects, always specify the target project in your trigger
        message (e.g. "set up a Figma file in the Myprotein Design project for the basket redesign").
        If the file ends up in the wrong place, it's easier to move it in Figma manually than to
        re-run the agent.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Competitor research step takes longer than expected.</strong>
        The competitor sweep visits 4–5 URLs in sequence. This typically takes 2–4 minutes. If
        a competitor site is slow or blocking the headless browser, the agent will skip it and note
        that it was skipped — the rest of the setup continues normally.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>No existing UX review for the page type you're redesigning.</strong>
        If there's no UX review in the repo for your target page, the agent will note this in the
        brief and suggest running a <code>/myprotein-ux-review</code> first. You can do this before
        starting the redesign, or run the prep agent now and do the review separately — either order
        works.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Brief doesn't reflect your actual constraints.</strong>
        The drafted brief is a starting point, not a final document. Edit it directly in Figma on
        the Cover page. The most important thing is that the competitor screenshots and UX findings
        are already in place — the brief text is the easiest part to adjust yourself.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style>
  .agent-intro { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .agent-eyebrow {
    font-size: 12px;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.1em;
    color: var(--color-primary);
    opacity: 0.5;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  .agent-h1 {
    font-size: clamp(26px, 4vw, 38px);
    font-weight: 800;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    line-height: 1.15;
  }
  .agent-summary {
    font-size: 15px;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    max-width: 680px;
  }

  .guide-section { margin-bottom: 52px; }
  .section-heading {
    font-size: 20px;
    font-weight: 800;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    padding-bottom: 10px;
    border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0,57,66,0.08);
  }
  .sub-heading {
    font-size: 14px;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin: 20px 0 8px;
  }

  .guide-body {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }
  .guide-body--tip {
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-mint);
    padding: 10px 14px;
    border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0;
    margin-top: 12px;
  }

  .checklist {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
  }
  .checklist li {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    padding-left: 22px;
    position: relative;
  }
  .checklist li::before {
    content: '→';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-primary);
    opacity: 0.4;
    font-size: 13px;
  }

  .trigger-block { margin-bottom: 16px; }
  .trigger-command {
    display: inline-block;
    font-size: 15px;
    font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
    background: var(--color-primary);
    color: var(--color-mint);
    padding: 8px 18px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.01em;
  }
  .trigger-examples {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 8px;
    margin-bottom: 14px;
  }
  .trigger-chip {
    font-size: 13px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    border: var(--card-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-chip);
    padding: 5px 12px;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    font-style: italic;
  }

  code {
    font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
    font-size: 12.5px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    color: var(--color-primary);
    padding: 2px 6px;
    border-radius: 4px;
  }

  .code-block {
    font-family: 'SF Mono', 'Fira Code', monospace;
    font-size: 13px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    padding: 16px 20px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    line-height: 1.7;
    overflow-x: auto;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    border: var(--card-border);
    white-space: pre;
  }

  .steps { list-style: none; display: flex; flex-direction: column; }
  .step {
    display: flex;
    gap: 20px;
    align-items: flex-start;
    padding: 24px 0;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(0,57,66,0.08);
  }
  .step:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .step-number {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    width: 34px;
    height: 34px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--color-primary);
    color: var(--color-mint);
    font-size: 13px;
    font-weight: 800;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    margin-top: 2px;
  }
  .step-title {
    font-size: 15px;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }
  .step-desc {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
  }

  .no-example {
    font-size: 14px;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    border: var(--card-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-card);
    padding: 16px 20px;
    font-style: italic;
    opacity: 0.8;
  }

  .tips-list {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 16px;
  }
  .tips-list li {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--color-text-body);
    background: var(--color-bg-card);
    border: var(--card-border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-card);
    padding: 16px 18px;
  }
  .tips-list strong {
    display: block;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
    margin-bottom: 4px;
  }
</style>
